# Lab Name
Reflected XSS into a JavaScript string with angle brackets HTML encoded

## Vulnerability
Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) – Reflected XSS

## Objective
Exploit a reflected XSS vulnerability by breaking out of a JavaScript string and executing arbitrary JavaScript.

## Entry Point
Search functionality

## Exploitation Type
Reflected XSS / JavaScript Context Injection

## Methodology
1. Open the lab and locate the search functionality

2. Submit a normal search request

3. Observe that the search term is reflected inside a JavaScript string

4. Notice that angle brackets (< and >) are HTML-encoded, preventing direct script tag injection

5. Since the input is placed inside a JavaScript string, break out of the string context

6. Inject JavaScript code followed by a comment to prevent syntax errors

7. Submit the payload through the search parameter

8. Load the response page

9. Observe that the injected JavaScript executes successfully

## Payload Used

'-alert(1)-'

## Result
Successfully executed arbitrary JavaScript by breaking out of a JavaScript string context.

## Impact
- Execution of arbitrary JavaScript
- Session hijacking
- Cookie theft
- Phishing attacks
- Account compromise

## Mitigation
- Properly escape user input before inserting it into JavaScript contexts
- Use context-aware output encoding
- Avoid dynamically generating JavaScript with user input
- Implement Content Security Policy (CSP)
- Validate and sanitize all user-controlled input

## Learning
HTML encoding angle brackets alone does not prevent XSS.
When user input is reflected inside JavaScript strings, attackers can break out of the string and inject arbitrary JavaScript if special characters are not properly escaped.
